\begin_layout Standard
Status is a complex sociological phenomenon.
 Often viewed as a static trait that depends on family or identity, one
 can assume that it is fixed over any reasonable time period for an econometric
 study.
 The rapid changes in wealth in all industrialized countries however have
 made such traditional notions of status rather obsolete.
 Even though statisticians have not yet adopted a standard measurement criterion
 for socio-economic status, SES is often proxied with occupation, education,
 income and family relationships (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NCVHS,PsakiSeidman2013,DiemerMistry2013"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Studies in health and welfare have built wealth indices to model SES.
 Of particular interest is the use of asset indices that track assets owned
 during the lifetime to measure SES.
 Our goal in the current study is not to comment on the methodologies used
 in measuring SES but to understand how the factors driving socio-economic
 status can influence non-durable consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our definition of status does not deviate much from literature.
 Defined in terms of wealth and assets, SES is sensitive to rise in incomes
 and in asset ownership.
 If the accumulation of assets is rapid, it is likely to influence the non-durab
le consumption in the short run for a population of consumers as well.
 We thus explore the relationship of ownership of assets with non-durable
 consumption over time to explain its effect on what one may consider the
 status-related consumption in the developing countries.
 We believe that the intertemporal life-cycle model should link the two
 bodies of literature i) on socio-economic status measurement and ii) on
 conspicuous consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We reject Veblen's notion of the futility of conspicuous consumption on
 grounds of measurability of consumption - arguing that the items of conspicuous
 consumption can bring status utility primarily by indicating the high assets
 worth of the owners of the such items (endowments and/or identities).
 The items of conspicuous consumption are futile in the sense only that
 they don't have any value except through the high net asset worth of their
 owners.
 With the definition of status in terms of occupation, education, assets
 and identity, we thus measure the changes in asset ownership with respect
 to age, income, region, occupation, education to answer how quickly the
 indicators of SES may change in a developing economy.
\end_layout

