\begin_layout Standard
An econometric analysis of items that presumably improve the status of its
 buyer can lead to a tautological problem.
 If status-items are items that indicate the status of the buyer, then what
 conclusions are there to be derived from the observed high consumption
 on status items other than that the buyers of status items have high status?
 Such a paradox is resolved quickly by considering that status if formed
 through expectation of change in future based on the wealth accumulated
 from past generations.
 This problem has been addressed much before the introduction of game-theoretica
l approaches in microeconomics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Veblen's treatise
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset

 on conspicuous consumption one such work that has inspired many studies
 after itself.
 As such a study predates the times when household surveys were formalised
 in their post-war form, a lot of claims from Veblen (or on conspicuous
 consumption in the literature) are less obvious to verify.
 Veblen's claim of the futility as the character of conspicuous consumption
 is not alone in this regard.
 Much later, commenting on the post-war developments in the Western society,
 Frederich Hirsch has argued that the human needs have expanded manifolds
 since the time when Adam Smith's invisible hand was known to work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits,GalbraithAffluent"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the rich pursuing their interests while poor gain social mobility
 is an exchange that no longer work in the modern society as it did in Europe
 of the eighteenth century when the offer for social mobility was far more
 lucrative.
 THe changes in inequality can be verified quite easily with the data.
 The view of industrial developments as a legacy of the race amongst the
 middle classes to achieve the higher social positions once held by the
 feudal elite - is one that is shared by many economists and sociologists
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits,SchumpeterCapitalism"

\end_inset

 - but there remains a lot in Hirsch's claims that is difficult to verify.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hirsch goes on to suggest that status differentials were necessary to create
 new markets - where positional goods and advertisement have a major role
 to play.
 The model he suggests for positional competition is not a very quantitative
 one and is reproduced in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:HirschsModel"

\end_inset

.
 With the physical scarcity of goods (food and amenities) largely conquered,
 he argued that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

scarcity
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 becomes largely social in the developed countries.
 More commercialization (availability of previous unavailable items through
 money) leads to more scarcities and more competitions - hence instances
 of congestion (high demand with little chance of fulfilment) for a good
 develop - leading to increased status or positional competition in the
 society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key issue in developing an empirical understanding the relationship between
 congestion and scarcity is of semantic nature.
 Scarcity seems a more general concept than mere unavailability or low supply
 of an item - as it seems to entail both unavailability of the item and
 the competition for it.
 Hirsch does differentiate between the physical scarcity (unavailability)
 and social scarcity (competition) but he also concludes that the boundary
 between physical and social scarcities can get blurred as the positional
 goods create a market for themselves.
 It is difficult to measure scarcity for a product or a range of products
 when the term encompasses both the physical scarcity (unavailability) and
 the perceived scarcity (what we feel as scarce).
 A consumer may indeed feel that the item is scarce because she cannot afford
 it or because the supply of the item is limited through some other mechanism
 (i.e.
 barriers exist in the distribution of the item).
  While such felt scarcities appear relevant for consumption, we can only
 measure them relevant if they arise out of a relevant physical scarcity.
 Instead of attempting to define or measure felt scarcities themselves (as
 is done in a subject survey), we expand the notion of the physical scarcity
 to include barriers created through status competitions, advertising or
 other social-psychological communication that create the sense of urgent
 demand for a status-carrying good.
 The fusion of physical and social scarcities does not seem a mathematically
 tractable idea.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another notion difficult to find an econometric equivalent of is the “scarcity
 through overuse” (which is emphasized as the engine of social scarcity
 in the modern Western society).
 Ambiguous as it may seem, it is even less relevant in the developing world
 where there simply aren't enough items to be consumed (likely a case of
 physical scarcity - using Hirsch's terminology) and all overuse could continue
 to be a luxury.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even so, Hirsch's ideas of scarcity and congestion are relevant in the developin
g countries (scarcity being the lack of supply or unavailability of a particular
 commodity while congestion being the changes in income levels within social
 groups).
 The goal of status-related consumption in a developing economy - as much
 as anywhere else - is to allow a given population of individuals to associate
 themselves to those with perceived higher status (due to direct income
 or otherwise) in society.
 Due to the problems mentioned above, the measurement and verification of
 the cultural trends identified by both Hirsch and Veblen become far from
 trivial.
 Even if we were provided the access to a reliable microdata on consumption
 sampled over varied social identities and extending over a period of decades,
 it is difficult to track and measure the nature of connections between
 individuals and the influences social groups have on each other.
 
\end_layout

