\begin_layout Section

\size large
Model for Status
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our model is quite similar to one used by Coreno et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

 - one that considers a ranking function for every individual so that consumptio
n is seen as a way to transform the income ranking of a population i.e.
 individuals improve their perception in society through consumption to
 overcome their income rank in the society.
 It can be argued that anyone in less than the highest income group (more
 specifically -the highest quantile of the all status determinants minus
 that of consumption) would benefit from a short-term expense on status-related
 consumption.
 Therefore, if conspicuous consumption does exist in a society, one can
 claim that the rank of expenditure on expendable items (or utility) and
 assets rank (or utility) must differ for the consumers in medium quantiles
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This verification may serve as the test of conspicuous consumption (the
 inference is equivalent to one that can be drawn from the permanent income
 elasticity of consumption of a certain item within different quantiles
 of a population).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 An econometric method can be derived from a status utility decomposed into
 the status utility through asset ownership and consumption of high-price
 items.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In other words, the status ranking that is imparted to an individual can
 be seen as a combination of a ranking of expenses on non-durable items
 and that of asset ownership.
 A key difference in our model is that unlike in the Ireland and Corneo
 models, we assume that all consumption items can impart status and focus
 on assets and high-priced items.
 The empirical problems of finding a clear boundary between conspicuous
 and non-conspicuous items is thus circumvented by relying on price and
 long-term ownership as the key determinants of status.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An analysis of the time-series data across multiple geographies (e.g.
 a quantile regression on a time-series of purchases across several income
 quantiles of the population) can further test whether consumers with different
 income ranks within a society do engage in pecuniary emulation or not.
 For now, however, we limit our focus on a cross-sectional analysis of data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
To calibrate a status utility function one can either split the consumer
 basket into positional (status) and non-positional (non-status) items (as
 is done in most of empirical work) or assign a status-utility to every
 commodity in the basket.
 For reasons discussed in the sections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ScarcityAndVisibility"

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Status-and-asset-ownership"

\end_inset

, we choose the latter option.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A consequence of assigning status potential to all items in the model is
 that the status utility can no longer be viewed as separable overall from
 the non-status part of utility (there are no purely status goods any more).
 In this preliminary model used for the empirical work, the consumer utility
 (comprising of status and non-status utility) is considered separable across
 functional groups such as food, energy, entertainment etc.
 in the usual sense - and the status items are chosen by the consumer within
 each category instead of as a separate category.
 This can be viewed as a two-state budgeting model for the separable functional
 groups - wherein the representative consumer first allocates money to be
 spent for the different functional categories (food, energy, etc.) and the
 overall status - before deciding on which status items to buy within each
 category (in food, energy, entertainment etc.).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The snob and bandwagon items - although not strictly equivalent to the two
 balancing tendencies of the consumer to buy assets and high-priced non-durable
 items - can also be understood in the model.
 The representative consumer chooses a snob item to protect her position
 in the societal ranking and use a bandwagon item to promote herself in
 the ranking.
 Both non-durable items and assets can be of snob or bandwagon type.
 It is the relative positioning in the social ranking - we argue - that
 determines whether a new item is snob or bandwagon type.
 For a particular consumer, the goal of protecting one's rank with a snob
 item is achieved by choosing the higher priced items in a category (thus
 entering a barrier to status) and the goal of advancing one's rank is achieved
 by acquiring an asset that associates oneself to someone who has a higher
 rank (thus directly acquiring an asset) .
 The consumer balances between the tendency to choose non-durable expenditure
 for an asset that is not affordable with that of expenditure on durable
 assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we decompose status utility into several functional categories, we also
 need to detail how choices for status in every functional category combine
 into the final status utility.
 In the long-run, we argue that the representative consumer develops a preferenc
e order of functional groups - food may become less important than housing
 and personal products etc.
 (as is indeed observed by the literature on visible consumption).
 At any given time, therefore, the representative consumer allocates her
 expenditure based on this preference of categories.
 The final status utility is aggregated over all the separable categories.
 For example, a consumer could acquire status by decorating his house or
 buying expensive cigars.
 Both housing and entertainment provide utility in the usual sense but paintings
 and cigars enhance status by letting the consumer derive status sub-utility
 from both housing and entertainment.
 The aggregation of sub-utilities in the categories is assumed to be linear
 - so that the total status utility is a weighted sum of status derived
 from every category.
 More details on this are provided in a later chapter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Status in this model is thus influenced predominantly by the price differences
 (let's call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

) and asset distribution (let's call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

).
 The effect of changes in prices, introduction of new items and visibility
 preferences are all through 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

.
 The mechanisms are affecting status are discussed in the next subsections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
