\begin_layout Subsection

\size normal
Effect of the distribution of assets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That acquiring long-term assets is the surest way to ascertain one's status
 in society is one of the key assumptions of our model for status
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The definition of asset is driven by consumer's intent of permanent ownership.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 For others to associate with such asset owners, the consumers are likely
 to own what they may fit within their budget.
 Despite the same monthly expenditure, for example, rented housing for the
 same cost may carry more status simply because the houses that are less
 affordable to own can be made affordable by offering as rental housing.
 Thus market forces presenting the consumer with cheaper substitutes can
 facilitate the status need fulfillment.
 In the case of housing (or transport etc.
 as the case may be) the consumer doesn't need to own the house (i.e.
 she does not need to pay the full-price of the item desired) but is able
 to signal more status than through owning a less expensive house (item)
 by simply renting the house (or the respective item).
 In general, wherever posed with the choice between owning and consuming
 the same item, the consumers may prefer to fulfill short-term status needs
 (in hope of future mobility) instead of owning either a high-price asset
 (which would require saving until a longer time) or a lower-priced asset
 (which would have significantly lower status advantage).
 This is simply because the markets may address status needs sooner than
 they address long-term needs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While our preference for understanding status consumption as the owning
 assets and short-term consumption is more measurable than the difference
 between status and non-status items, we are aware that the difference between
 assets and monthly consumption is not without problems.
 For example, the status utility from monthly expenditure and that from
 owning assets are not always independent of one another.
 There would always exist items for monthly consumption that are either
 closely related or are substitutes of the corresponding owned assets.
 The status utility from electricity in a developing country, for example,
 would be achieved not only by having access to electricity but also (and
 more so) by running other appliances that depend on electricity.
 More expenditure on electricity doesn't derive so status by itself as it
 does by letting the consumer use owned or rented assets that run on electricity.
 The status utility (or ranking) from monthly expenditure therefore depends
 very much on the related assets in such a case.
 In case of mortgages, as another example, the boundary between asset ownership
 and monthly expenditure gets blurred.
 The status utility from assets and consumption cannot be considered separable
 (or independent of each other) in the model of status based on assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The issues of supply (availability) are prevalent in assets as well.
 As the consumption of a lot of items are dependent on each other - thus
 they are forgone collectively.
 In other words, the status disadvantage from not consuming an item 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 may add up towards the disadvantage from not consuming 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 if the consumption on 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is dependent on consuming the item 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 For example, the status disadvantage from not consuming electricity may
 include the disadvantage of not having AC, stereo speakers etc.
 In reality, when the consumers in an area don't have access to electricity,
 they lose collectively in the status hierarchy simply by being residents
 of the region.
 In such a case, it's there is simply no opportunity to overspend on electricity
 to emulate those who have electricity.
\end_layout

